   "source": [
    "### Part C Short Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "In Part C, we used spaCy en_core_web_lg embeddings to convert each post into a vector, and then trained a Logistic Regression model.\n",
    "\n",
    "The model achieved a test accuracy of 0.92, which is much higher than 0.66 in Part B (VADER). This shows that Part C performs much better.\n",
    "\n",
    "The reason is that VADER is a rule-based model and mainly looks at sentiment (positive or negative). However, toxicity is more complicated than sentiment. Some toxic posts may not look very negative, so VADER can miss them. This is why Part B had low recall for toxic posts.\n",
    "\n",
    "In Part C, we used pre-trained embeddings, which can capture more meaning from the text. Then the Logistic Regression model learns patterns from the training data. Because of this, the model can classify both toxic and non-toxic posts more accurately.\n",
    "\n",
    "From the results, we can see that Part C improves both:\n",
    "\n",
    "- detecting toxic posts correctly, and\n",
    "- avoiding wrong predictions on non-toxic posts\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, Part C shows that using embeddings with a supervised model works much better than a simple rule-based method.\n",
    "\n",
    "One limitation is that spaCy embeddings are still general-purpose, so they may not fully understand slang or informal language in social media.\n",
    "\n",
    "### How Part C satisfies the project requirement\n",
    "This part achieves the requirement by:\n",
    "1. converting each post into a vector using **`en_core_web_lg`**,\n",
    "2. training **Logistic Regression** on the training embeddings,\n",
    "3. predicting on the test embeddings,\n",
    "4. and reporting the **accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report**.\n"
   ]
